</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BAD36803D6D5D27A8BBF0DF16CFFEBA" blockId="34.[151,1437,151,751]" pageId="34" pageNumber="335">
<emphasis id="B966EA923D6D5D27A8BBF0DF13B5FF6E" bold="true" box="[199,462,151,176]" pageId="34" pageNumber="335">External morphology.</emphasis>
This spectacular, relatively large 
<taxonomicName id="4C124D033D6D5D27AB32F0D011E1FF71" box="[846,922,152,175]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="335" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B966EA923D6D5D27AB32F0D011E1FF71" box="[846,922,152,175]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="335">Myotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a unique cottony and yellowish fur, both above and below, the dorsal parts being only slightly darker at the hair tips (i.e., no ”smoked” aspect of fur as in 
<taxonomicName id="4C124D033D6D5D27AD01F0F5137AFF26" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="335" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rufoniger">
<emphasis id="B966EA923D6D5D27AD01F0F5137AFF26" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="335">M. rufoniger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The wing membranes are parti-colored, with a characteristic orange (along bones) and black patterning (see pictures in 
<bibRefCitation id="EF834B713D6D5D27A933F14C107AFEC2" author="Lin" box="[335,513,260,285]" pageId="34" pageNumber="335" refString="Lin, L. K., Lee, L. L. &amp; Cheng, H. C. (2004) Bats of Taiwan (2 nd ed.). National Museum of Natural Sciences, Taipei, 177 pp. [in Chinese]" type="book" year="2004">
Lin 
<emphasis id="B966EA923D6D5D27A9FCF14D13C0FEC2" box="[384,443,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="335">et al.</emphasis>
<number id="3DDA24A73D6D5D27A9B8F14C107AFEC2" box="[452,513,260,284]" pageId="34" pageNumber="335" value="2004.0">2004</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). The uropatagium is essentially orange, as are the ears (unlike in 
<taxonomicName id="4C124D033D6D5D27AD78F14D17EEFEC2" box="[1284,1429,260,284]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="335" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rufoniger">
<emphasis id="B966EA923D6D5D27AD78F14D17EEFEC2" box="[1284,1429,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="335">M. rufoniger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which has conspicuous black margins to the ears) and face. Thumbs and hairy feet are also largely orange, except close to the claws, which are strong and black. Wings are attached to the base of the outer toe.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BAD36803D6D5D27A8BBF1271759FE2A" blockId="34.[151,1437,151,751]" pageId="34" pageNumber="335">
<emphasis id="B966EA923D6D5D27A8BBF12713D8FE56" bold="true" box="[199,419,367,392]" pageId="34" pageNumber="335">Skull morphology.</emphasis>
The skull is large, with massive canines and strong molars. The second upper premolar is much smaller, less than half the size of the first, and is usually completely displaced lingually from toothrow and thus invisible in side view (
<figureCitation id="13292A053D6D5D27A9B4F1FF1071FE0E" box="[456,522,439,464]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="31.[151,250,1954,1976]" captionTargetBox="[176,1411,193,1931]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[176,1411,193,1933]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 8. Lateral and dorsal views of skull, and mandible of (a) Myotis soror sp. n. (HNHM 2003.36. 20., holotype), (b) M. frater (TESRI B 0283), (c) M. formosus (THUMB 65), and (d) M. rufoniger (THUMB 30022). All specimens are from Taiwan. Scale = 10 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3924056" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3924056/files/figure.png" pageId="34" pageNumber="335">
Fig. 
<number id="3DDA24A73D6D5D27A980F1F01071FE0E" box="[508,522,440,464]" pageId="34" pageNumber="335" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
c). The posterior parts of the braincase are high and globose, with very weak or no occipital or lambdoid crests (unlike in 
<taxonomicName id="4C124D033D6D5D27AA3BF19510AEFE2A" box="[583,725,476,500]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="335" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rufoniger">
<emphasis id="B966EA923D6D5D27AA3BF19510AEFE2A" box="[583,725,476,500]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="335">M. rufoniger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which has a more angular skull and marked crests).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BAD36803D6D5D27A8BBF1B7129AFD31" blockId="34.[151,1437,151,751]" pageId="34" pageNumber="335">
<emphasis id="B966EA923D6D5D27A8BBF1B713F0FDC6" bold="true" box="[199,395,511,536]" pageId="34" pageNumber="335">Natural History.</emphasis>
This beautiful, but rare bat is known from few specimens, and owing to its large distribution across Asia is likely to have different ecologies throughout its range. In 
<collectingCountry id="F30576103D6D5D27AB94F26C1646FDE3" box="[1000,1085,548,573]" name="Taiwan" pageId="34" pageNumber="335">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
, it is found exclusively in the lowlands, where it roosts either among tree foliage (
<bibRefCitation id="EF834B713D6D5D27AA90F20F11EFFDBE" author="Swinhoe" box="[748,916,583,608]" pageId="34" pageNumber="335" refString="Swinhoe, R. (1870) Catalogue of the mammals of China (south of the River Yangtsze) and of the island of Formosa. Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London, 42, 615 - 652." type="journal article" year="1870">
Swinhoe 
<number id="3DDA24A73D6D5D27AB25F20011EFFDBE" box="[857,916,584,608]" pageId="34" pageNumber="335" value="1870.0">1870</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; Chen 
<emphasis id="B966EA923D6D5D27AB99F2011664FDBE" box="[997,1055,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="335">et al.</emphasis>
<number id="3DDA24A73D6D5D27AC54F200161FFDBE" box="[1064,1124,584,608]" pageId="34" pageNumber="335" value="2010.0">2010</number>
), or in buildings (
<bibRefCitation id="EF834B713D6D5D27AD4DF20F12AFFD5A" author="Lin" pageId="34" pageNumber="335" refString="Lin, L. K., Lee, L. L. &amp; Cheng, H. C. (2004) Bats of Taiwan (2 nd ed.). National Museum of Natural Sciences, Taipei, 177 pp. [in Chinese]" type="book" year="2004">
Lin 
<emphasis id="B966EA923D6D5D27AD1EF20117E7FDBE" box="[1378,1436,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="335">et al.</emphasis>
<number id="3DDA24A73D6D5D27A8EBF22412AFFD5A" box="[151,212,620,644]" pageId="34" pageNumber="335" value="2004.0">2004</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). In both situations, the bats are fully exposed to the light and seem to rely on their particular coloration to avoid predation. They occupy the breeding colonies (which may number up to several hundred individuals) between March and July. In October, they disappear from the breeding colonies to hibernate in unknown winter roosts.
</paragraph>
